    <script>
        // Dark mode detection
        if (window.matchMedia && window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches) {
            document.documentElement.classList.add('dark');
        }
        window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').addEventListener('change', event => {
            if (event.matches) {
                document.documentElement.classList.add('dark');
            } else {
                document.documentElement.classList.remove('dark');
            }
        });

        // Curriculum Data
        const modules = [
            {
                id: 1,
                title: "AI Foundations",
                goal: "Build confidence without overwhelming learners",
                sections: [
                    {
                        title: "What AI Actually Is (and Isn't)",
                        icon: "fa-lightbulb",
                        content: `<p>Artificial intelligence (AI) refers to computational systems designed to perform tasks that typically require human cognition—such as pattern recognition, language generation, and decision support—by learning from large datasets. AI operates through mathematical models and statistical inference, not awareness or understanding.</p>
                        <p>It does not possess consciousness, intent, emotions, or independent reasoning. Even when AI outputs appear insightful or creative, they are the result of probabilistic pattern matching rather than genuine comprehension.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box tip">
                            <strong>Key Insight:</strong> Understanding this prevents over-trust and reinforces AI's role as a tool that augments human thinking rather than replacing it.
                        </div>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Generative AI, LLMs, Tools vs Models",
                        icon: "fa-layer-group",
                        content: `<p><strong>Generative AI</strong> is a category of AI systems designed to produce new content—such as text, images, audio, or code—rather than simply analyzing existing data.</p>
                        <p><strong>Large Language Models (LLMs)</strong> are a subset of generative AI trained specifically on vast amounts of text to predict and generate human-like language.</p>
                        <p>An <strong>AI model</strong> is the underlying trained system that performs these predictions, while an <strong>AI tool</strong> is the user-facing application built on top of one or more models.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box">
                            Tools add structure, interfaces, safeguards, and workflows, meaning the same model can behave very differently depending on how the tool is designed and constrained.
                        </div>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Common Myths & Limitations",
                        icon: "fa-exclamation-triangle",
                        content: `<p>A widespread myth is that AI is inherently accurate, objective, or authoritative. In practice, AI can produce convincing but incorrect responses, reflect biases present in its training data, and lack real-world awareness or up-to-date information.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box warning">
                            <strong>Critical Understanding:</strong> AI does not verify truth; it predicts plausibility.
                        </div>
                        <p>These limitations require users to critically evaluate outputs, cross-check information, and apply human judgment. Over-reliance on AI without verification can lead to misinformation, shallow understanding, and flawed decision-making.</p>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Ethical Use & Academic Honesty",
                        icon: "fa-balance-scale",
                        content: `<p>Ethical AI use—especially in academic contexts—centers on transparency, responsibility, and learning integrity. AI can be appropriately used for brainstorming, outlining, feedback, and skill practice, but submitting AI-generated content as original work undermines educational goals and violates academic honesty policies.</p>
                        <p>Ethical use requires understanding institutional guidelines, disclosing AI assistance when required, and ensuring that AI supports—not substitutes—original thinking.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box tip">
                            When used responsibly, AI becomes a powerful learning aid; when misused, it compromises both skill development and credibility.
                        </div>`
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                id: 2,
                title: "Prompt Engineering Basics",
                goal: "Teach users how prompts control output",
                sections: [
                    {
                        title: "Anatomy of a Prompt",
                        icon: "fa-dna",
                        content: `<p>An effective prompt is a structured set of instructions that guides an AI system toward a specific, usable output. The five key components are:</p>
                        <p><strong>Role</strong> defines the perspective or expertise the AI should adopt (e.g., tutor, analyst, editor), shaping tone and depth.</p>
                        <p><strong>Task</strong> clearly states what the AI is being asked to do, eliminating ambiguity about the goal.</p>
                        <p><strong>Context</strong> provides background information, audience details, or situational constraints that narrow the response space and improve relevance.</p>
                        <p><strong>Constraints</strong> set boundaries—such as length, style, sources, or complexity—which reduce off-target or overly generic outputs.</p>
                        <p><strong>Output Format</strong> specifies how the response should be presented (bullet points, table, paragraph, step-by-step), ensuring the result is immediately usable without additional editing.</p>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Why Vague Prompts Fail",
                        icon: "fa-times-circle",
                        content: `<p>Vague prompts fail because AI systems optimize for plausibility, not intent. When instructions lack clarity, the model fills in gaps by relying on generalized patterns from training data, often producing broad, surface-level responses that miss the user's actual objective.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box warning">
                            Ambiguity in task definition, missing context, or undefined expectations forces the AI to guess, increasing the likelihood of irrelevant, inaccurate, or inconsistent outputs.
                        </div>
                        <p>Precision in prompting reduces cognitive "search space" for the model, leading to higher-quality, more predictable results.</p>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Prompt Iteration & Refinement",
                        icon: "fa-sync-alt",
                        content: `<p>Prompting is an iterative process rather than a one-time command. Initial outputs should be evaluated for accuracy, depth, and alignment with the intended goal, then refined by adjusting roles, adding constraints, or clarifying context.</p>
                        <p>Small changes—such as specifying audience level or requesting justification—can significantly improve output quality.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box tip">
                            Expert prompt users treat AI interactions as guided conversations, progressively narrowing and shaping responses through feedback and revision.
                        </div>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "Zero-Shot vs Few-Shot Prompts",
                        icon: "fa-crosshairs",
                        content: `<p><strong>Zero-shot prompts</strong> provide instructions without examples, relying on the model's prior training to infer the task. They are efficient for simple or well-defined requests but can produce inconsistent results for complex tasks.</p>
                        <p><strong>Few-shot prompts</strong> include one or more examples that demonstrate the desired output style or reasoning process, significantly improving accuracy and consistency.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box">
                            By showing the model what "good" looks like, few-shot prompting reduces ambiguity and aligns outputs more closely with user expectations.
