                        title: "The RACE Framework",
                        icon: "fa-flag-checkered",
                        content: `<p>The RACE Framework emphasizes clarity and alignment through four components:</p>
                        <p><strong>Role</strong> establishes the expertise or perspective the AI should assume, shaping tone and depth.</p>
                        <p><strong>Action</strong> defines the specific task to be performed, ensuring the model understands the objective.</p>
                        <p><strong>Context</strong> provides situational details, background information, or audience characteristics that guide relevance.</p>
                        <p><strong>Expectation</strong> specifies quality standards, level of detail, and output format.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box">
                            Together, these components create a balanced prompt that is both directive and flexible, making RACE particularly effective for analytical, educational, and professional tasks.
                        </div>`
                    },
                    {
                        title: "The CRISP Framework",
                        icon: "fa-gem",
                        content: `<p>The CRISP Framework focuses on precision and constraints. It typically includes:</p>
                        <p><strong>C</strong>ontext • <strong>R</strong>equirements • <strong>I</strong>nstructions • <strong>S</strong>tyle • <strong>P</strong>resentation</p>
                        <p>CRISP prompts are especially useful when outputs must adhere to strict guidelines, such as word limits, formatting rules, or tonal requirements.</p>
                        <div class="highlight-box tip">
                            By explicitly stating how the response should look and what it must include or exclude, CRISP minimizes irrelevant information and increases consistency across outputs.
